y study, Julie Feinsilver explores the Cuban medical phenomenon, examining how a governmental obsession with health has reaped medical and political benefits at home and abroad. As a result of Cuba's forward strides in health care, infant mortality rates are low even by First World standards. Cuba has successfully dealt with the AIDS epidemic in a manner that has aroused controversy and that some claim has infringed on individual liberties—issues that Feinsilver succinctly evaluates.Feinsilver's research and travel in Cuba over many years give her a unique perspective on the challenges Cuba faces in this time of unprecedented economic and political uncertainty. Her book is a must-read for everyone concerned with health policy, international relations, and Third World societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMedical assistance, CubanxPolitical aspects. 0aMedical carexPolitical aspectszCuba. 0aMedical care. 0aMedical policyzCuba. 0aMedical policy. 0aPolitics, Practical. 0aSymbolism in politicszCuba. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh  a20th century cuban history.  a20th century cuban politics.  abiomedical research.  abiotechnology.  acastro.  acommunism.  acuba.  acuban health care system.  adisaster relief.  afidel castro.  agovernment and governing.  ahealth care.  ahealth education.  ahealth.  alatin american history.  amedical care.  amedical diplomacy.  amedical pharmaceutical exports.  apolicy studies.  apolitical views.  apublic health professionals.  apublic health system.  arevolution.  asocial policy.  auniversal health care.  aworld medical power.  aworld medicine.1 aApter, David E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package 